 **1254454529*Leverage memo "Effective Time Management"
 <a href="http://www.amazon.co.jp/gp/product/4537256842?ie=UTF8&tag=nishiohirokaz-22&linkCode=as2&camp=247&creative=7399& creativeASIN=4537256842">Effective Time Management&#8212;Maximize Work Efficiency The Yashiro 15 Minute Work Method</a><img src="http://www.assoc-amazon.jp/e/ir?t= nishiohirokaz-22&l=as2&o=9&a=4537256842" width="1" height="1" border="0" alt="" style="border:none !important; margin:0px !important;" />
 
 It is not because of a weak will that people make plans and fail to realize them. It is because they make reckless plans that can never be realized, and then they fall further and further behind schedule and give up when they can no longer accomplish the task no matter what they think. So, I think we should first set up a period of time to start the process, and then quantitatively measure how many tasks can be done in how much time. Indeed, looking back on my past experiences of failure, I realized that I had made plans without measuring how much I could accomplish.
 
 The other interesting classification is that there are some types of tasks that can be done in small chunks of time and some that can't. It's true that I can't do coding in 15 minutes. I used to play Othello (Morocco) on my iPhone when I had some free time on the train, but I was getting tired of it and thought that I should use this time to gather information or study. I'm wondering if there is an app that streams abst papers on iPhone.
 
 Below is the raw leverage memo
 <hr>
 Work is determined by shredded time.
 I really wanted to title it "The Golden Path to Semi-Retirement in Your 50s," but they objected.
 One cannot pursue efficiency alone.
 Is that "busyness" billable: is it billable work, who are you spending your time for?
 Time approach and volume approach: Tasks that are divided by time and tasks that are divided by volume, such as information gathering, can be finished because "an hour has passed," but for creative work, "the time has come, let's continue later" will worsen productivity. It is necessary to finish all tasks at once until the volume reaches a predetermined level. Do not include volume-approach tasks when there are important tasks behind. Time-approach tasks can be done even in small time slots.
 One way to do this is to put in the smallest amount of time what you are not bothered by spending time on and what you really want to study.
 What would you do if you had 15 minutes: I can't be creative. Gather information, study, etc. If you don't decide, it will be over while you are worrying.
 Planning is necessary to achieve your desires: First, measure your processing capacity as a number.
 Measure the time you are working with a stopwatch (properly excluding looking away or using the restroom).
 Two weeks as a helping period for the plan.
 There are higher ups. There are many people who do a better job in a shorter time. Don't aim for 100% yourself, but show others at 70%. The better you are at it, the faster you will be at it.
 Waste of time "thinking again what you once thought." Think as you write it down on paper.
 I read through five national newspapers, but it is impossible to read all of them. I read only the headlines and then read the articles in small chunks of time.
 People who have their past experiences categorized and organized in their minds are able to divert data and process it faster.
 Top Gear in the Morning: Prepare what you will do tomorrow during the night before
 It is okay to make holes in the plan because it cannot be followed perfectly, but the holes that are made must be properly cleaned up. Do not pretend that it did not happen. Reschedule appointments exactly as you would appointments with other people.
 Many people resolve to do something, but end up overdoing it for three days. Why is that? We did some research on people who have failed. They said, "I didn't have time," or "I got fed up because I didn't make any progress. There are "no plan" and "reckless plan. They are perfectionists and lose motivation as soon as they realize that they can't achieve their goals. They then become depressed and think, "I am a weak-willed person who can't even carry out the plans I made. It is not that you are weak-willed, but that you are making plans that cannot be realized due to a lack of planning ability. First, measure your processing capacity. Quantify. Set your plan a little higher and aim for 70%. Don't suddenly make a long-span plan; give yourself a two-week run-in period. Check the feasibility of the plan and whether you should do it in the first place. It may be tempting to cram too much into the plan, but that's okay during the run-up period. If you can confirm what you can't do because you've packed too much in, or if you can measure how far you've come, the purpose of the run-in period has been fulfilled. Next time, make a plan that looks doable. Let's prepare a time reserve, because there will be tasks that we won't know if we don't try them, and instead of worrying about the 30% that we didn't get done, let's get excited about the 70% that we did get done. Make a plan when your mind is saturated with studying, and don't use your core time to do it.
 Keep a table of tasks and fill them in with markers when completed. Accomplishment.
 Television is a subjective medium. There is much to be gained by simply looking at the headlines in a bookstore. A website where you can view train hanging ads: http://www.zassi.net/latest_ad_list.php
 When you look at a speed-reading expert's gaze, you are moving forward in the center of the book. The threshold for checking is low. Only extract the good parts to read over later.
 Start reading a book as soon as you purchase it. The moment you buy it is when you want to read it the most. If you give it time, it will fade away.
 Unlike paper, digital data is not "thrown away" because it doesn't take up space.
 Make a selection of first army notebooks. Watch the notebooks you make over and over again and memorize them on film.
 
