 Oh, I found the perfect thing to scan. There are about 140 sheets of presentation materials from the summer Prosin, of varying paper quality, depending on who you ask. If I throw them away, it will be impossible to get them later, but if I keep them in paper form and don't refer to them, then I won't refer to them. It's just perfect. I tried to put them all together for now, but they were too thick to scan. I tried separating them, but when the slippery paper is at the bottom, it is sucked in all at once and an error occurs. I decided to put the slippery paper at the top, and everything was scanned successfully.
 
 <img src="http://gyazo.com/8fb51390e491ac66b1e69eff2df0cf5b.png">
 
 Yeah, yeah, now I can throw it away without worry. I had a few jams only when there was slippery paper at the bottom, but it was not a problem because the jams were not the same as the old ADF, where the paper would get squishy and non-recursive, but simply because I sent multiple sheets and the "Failed! I've scanned about 140 sheets and only had about 2 failures.
 
 <hr>
 
 I thought the OCR time would be a distraction, but between scanning and OCR, I cut the next paper and so on... and it starts to speed up and doesn't stop. Oh man, this is addictive! I'm chopping papers all over the place without writing the papers that need to be written!
 
 <hr>
 I couldn't resist the desire and since I didn't have a cutter, I giggled with a cutter knife. I read it and made a leverage memo, saying it was a book I was going to throw away and I didn't care if it failed.
 
